  paragraphs:
  - Stop!
  - Ah! Who are you?
  - Those items, all that you have just taken... Hand them to me. They are not yours
    to take!
  - 'I beg your pardon! I''m a scholar, you see. From the Smithsonian Institution.
    Don''t be alarmed, I''m simply collecting specimens for educational purposes.

'
  - What you have taken from here, from this land...it belongs to my people! They
    have been here for thousands of years undisturbed!
  - 'And I assure you, these artifacts will be well cared for and studied properly.
    Surely you understand the importance of preserving your culture for future generations? '
  - These pieces will help educate people about your remarkable heritage. I'm afraid
    I must decline your offer.
  - Oh, is that so? Be cautious, child. The forest will not let you leave with stolen
    goods. It watches closely and always remembers.
  - What could a forest of trees and simple birds do against me? You speak nonsense.
  - You have my word these will be treated with reverence, but I must take my leave
    now. Science waits for no one, I'm afraid.
  - This is your final warning...please hand over what you took and return them at
    once! You are toying with powers beyond your means...
  - I'm afraid I don't share your superstitions, madam. Now, if you'll excuse me,
    I really must be going.
  - You have made your choice, traveler. The forest does not forget, and soon you
    shall discover why.
